    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_73184610" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/73184610" />
    <a title="Kim" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2795055-kim"><img alt="Kim" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1254487003p2/2795055.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/73184610?book_show_action=true">Oct 02, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kim" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kim" href="/user/show/2795055-kim">Kim</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer73184610" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6984588763158849351">This is, on the surface, a murder mystery. But it is set in a small town in South Africa, on the boarder with Mozambique, in 1952. The historical timing of the setting of the story immediately changes this novel from a mere murder mystery to a political comment. And I think it meets both challenges it sets itself very well.<br/><br/> <br/><br/>Detective Emmanuel Cooper is sent to investigate what is thought to be a hoax call in the small town of Jacob’s Rest. What he actually lands up investigating is the murder of</span>
  <span id="freeText6984588763158849351" style="display:none">This is, on the surface, a murder mystery. But it is set in a small town in South Africa, on the boarder with Mozambique, in 1952. The historical timing of the setting of the story immediately changes this novel from a mere murder mystery to a political comment. And I think it meets both challenges it sets itself very well.<br /><br /> <br /><br />Detective Emmanuel Cooper is sent to investigate what is thought to be a hoax call in the small town of Jacob’s Rest. What he actually lands up investigating is the murder of a senior white police officer. His investigation has him clashing with the staunch Afrikaans family that runs the town, the security Branch, the local non-white community which has very recently had to change its lifestyle because of the new regime ruling the country, and his own sense of right and wrong. <br /><br /> <br /><br />Throughout the story he struggles with being as good a man as he can. He is aware of his privilege based solely on his skin colour, but also knows there is little he can do about it. But all of the politics never detract from a jolly good story. I was dying to know who dunnit right up until we are told. <br /><br /> <br /><br />For readers not old enough to truly appreciate how things have changed in this country, this book will be a great read and maybe make you want to know more about what has happened in South Africa. If it doesn’t, it’s okay. As a straight forward murder mystery, A beautiful place to die is worth reading anyway.<br /><br /> <br /><br />For those of us old enough to have grown up in the old South Africa, this book will show you how far we sank; and how far we have come. I was amazed and ashamed and proud and riveted.<br /><br /> <br /><br />Worth reading<br />Worth buying if you have someone to pass it on to<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="6984588763158849351" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


